@@eMafdet: The Guardian Port@@N

Where the Saltglass Reach meets the open sea stands @@yMafdet@@N, the fortified
harbor that serves as the world's gateway between inland civilization and
ocean trade. The city takes its name from a protective figure of pre-Keeper
coastal ritual: a swift, feline executioner who punished oath-breakers. The
name carries an implicit promise -- justice here is swift and unsentimental.

@@yThe Guardian Naming Tradition@@N

Every citizen carries a @@yguardian-name@@N alongside their given name, a mark of
accountability inherited from the ancient watch cults. At the Shrine of the
First Claw, trade oaths are sealed upon a basalt sculpture worn smooth by
centuries of hands. Breaking such an oath is the gravest commercial crime
in the port.

@@gThe Dual-Attestation Protocol@@N

No cargo enters or leaves without verification under both @@ginland provenance@@N
and @@lmaritime risk@@N standards. The beach itself is a legal boundary where two
kinds of law are reconciled through the Shoreward Conversion.

@@dThe Ledger House and the Quarantine Ledger@@N

Four Ledger Houses certify manifests. The @@rQuarantine Ledger@@N, smallest but
most sensitive, classifies pyramid-origin artifacts by hazard level. Its
four-tier system descends directly from Khar'Daan's ancient containment
procedures -- in a real sense, its Hazard Scribes are Khar'Daan's last
functioning bureaucrats.

@@lThe Strandline Compact@@N

Three blocs share power: @@lHarbor Wardens@@N enforce quay security and the
harbor chain, @@yLedger Houses@@N certify documents and conversion rates, and
the @@dSand-Sea Carters' Guild@@N controls overland linkage to the oasis
corridors. No bloc dominates for long. The harbor's signal towers are the
first thing arriving ships see, and the Shrine's claw-marked spire the
second. Mafdet pays fairly, heals without prejudice, and never asks where
you came from -- only what you can carry.
